The study investigated whether an AI-assisted learning approach, incorporating a peer-driven, interactive, and AI-generated error-correction phase, enhanced students knowledge application and metacognitive awareness compared to AI self-learning followed by teacher summarization. It focused on biomedical materials education while addressing concerns about students uncritical acceptance of AI-generated content.

The researchers used a quasi-experimental, non-randomized pre-test–post-test design comparing a control group (AI self-learning plus teacher summarization) with an intervention group that additionally completed an interactive AI-generated error-correction activity. During this phase, students answered both teacher-recommended and self-generated questions by prompting an AI chatbot, then identified factual errors, omissions, or inaccuracies in the AIs responses using textbooks and reliable references before sharing and discussing their corrections with the class. Both groups completed the same AI-supported inquiry learning, with the error-correction activity replacing the teacher summarization phase for the intervention group.

- Students in the intervention group achieved significantly higher knowledge application scores than the control group after the intervention.
- The intervention produced significantly higher overall metacognitive awareness, with improvements across metacognitive knowledge, monitoring, and regulation.
- The learning approach promoted metacognitive monitoring by requiring students to evaluate AI outputs, detect errors, justify corrections, and regulate their own understanding during collaborative review.

The authors recommend integrating AI into higher education through structured, peer-driven error-correction activities that position AI as a fallible learning partner rather than an authoritative source. They emphasize embedding AI literacy within disciplinary learning through intentional instructional design that promotes critical evaluation and metacognitive development.
